00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.200
Again, thank you for the invitation, and we will continue our journey in marginal zone

00:00:05.200 --> 00:00:11.780
lymphoma, and we will discuss genomic landscape specifically of extranodal marginal zone lymphoma.

00:00:13.060 --> 00:00:16.840
So, as you know, extranodal marginal zone lymphoma is the most common marginal zone

00:00:16.840 --> 00:00:19.160
lymphoma, accounting for 61% of the cases.

00:00:19.660 --> 00:00:23.700
However, the mutational landscape of these extranodal marginal zone lymphoma cases has

00:00:23.700 --> 00:00:29.000
been only evaluated in small number of patients, and mainly by targeted sequencing, because

00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:32.240
most of these biopsies are usually very, very small or not accessible.

00:00:33.160 --> 00:00:38.900
Consequently, the comprehensive genomic landscape of this disease is largely unknown in contrast

00:00:38.900 --> 00:00:40.180
to many other lymphomas.

00:00:41.280 --> 00:00:49.320
So, we analyzed 177 samples from 175 patients from 20 academic hematological departments.

00:00:49.320 --> 00:00:55.800
We performed holoxone sequencing followed by targeted sequencing of 450 genes of potential

00:00:55.800 --> 00:00:58.840
tumor drivers in 165 patients.

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:02.200
Copy number variation were examined in 84 patients.

00:01:02.520 --> 00:01:05.740
RNA sequencing was performed in 159 patients.

00:01:06.080 --> 00:01:09.680
This is the largest study also for this, not done previously.

00:01:10.140 --> 00:01:15.300
Tumors from 17 locations were found, and that's also introduced heterogeneity.

00:01:15.740 --> 00:01:21.760
And the most common anatomic locations were ocular adnexa, gastric, including H. pylori

00:01:21.760 --> 00:01:25.720
positive and negative, salivary gland, and lungs.

00:01:27.220 --> 00:01:28.780
We identified 1,000 patients.

00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:39.220
2,218 variants across 174 genes, and 2,837 copy number of focal alterations.

00:01:39.220 --> 00:01:45.120
Combining DNA mutations and copy number alterations, the number of genetic lesions per tumor samples

00:01:45.120 --> 00:01:53.720
in the putative 174 putative driver genes averaged 25 per case, ranging from 0 to 102,

00:01:53.720 --> 00:01:58.000
which is consistent with previous genetic studies in other subtypes of marginal zone

00:01:58.000 --> 00:01:58.200
lymphoma, not all in specific.

00:01:58.200 --> 00:02:08.380
Of these genes, 44 and 11 were mutated in 5 or more than 10% of the analyzed specimens

00:02:08.380 --> 00:02:15.240
and may represent based on the nature of aberrations that were observed as driver genes.

